BEWARE of CHANGING PRICES! I came here recently and was asked to scan the menu with my phone. The menu item I inquired about read that 10 pieces of qebapa were 14.50. The waitress said she can split the 10 pieces into 5 each but when the bill came back she charged us separately for the 5 pieces at $18.50. She did not disclose to us that she would be charging us for this amount prior to us receiving the check. When this was pointed out the waitress defended her action and said « thats what the system had as the price » and did not change the check willingly or apologize to us or even show remorse. Terrible, misleading service. The food is OVERpriced! There are way better options for Albanian food at fraction of the cost. Youre getting ripped off the moment you step in! The portions are so SMALL. In addition the meat options are all VEAL! Which makes no sense because traditional Albanian cuisine rarely uses veal - instead it is meant to be beef. There were no other meat options. Save your money and research other places! Most importantly be aware of insidious service tricks! If youre getting your food to go, check that all items are there before you leave. I dont know why theres so many locations of this place when the original place has so many issues. We ended up paying the additional $4 and will not be returning! Last, it is CASH only but there are NO SIGNS anywhere for this! And we were not told until last moment.

A warm welcoming atmosphere  with wait staff clad in traditional Northern Albanian wear, this place offers delightful family style dining. Reminiscent of a hunting lodge with exposed brick and decor, the food is hearty and the portions plenty. Ingredients are fresh, and their freshly baked thick pita bread goes well with all else you will order. I’m a foodie that enjoys Ethiopian and South American food and snobbish when it comes to flavor, yet I loved the food here. Flavors were authentic just like the ones you would encounter in the Northern part of Albania. The food was outstanding in terms of flavor and presentation, it was definitely worth making the drive to the Bronx to enjoy a meal here with friends and family. I enjoyed the leftovers while thinking of a lovely time I had there. Next time we go, we are leaving room for their desserts which looked outstanding on the adjacent tables.

The food at Çka Ka Qellu is excellent. ... And better than most of the food we ate on a 10-day trip to Albania a few years ago. We ended up here after we made an unfortunate choice to meet friends and another restaurant on a day when Fordham football was playing and we couldn't get seating where we had planned. The clay pot dumplings with yogurt sauce are delicious. The "bread" (more like fat pita) is homemade and comes from the oven pipping hot. Sausages and salad were wonderful and we saw other diners with equally yummy looking food. The menu is meat heavy and not a great place if you have a vegetarian or someone who only eat seafood in the party. If they had 1-2 more veggie and fish/shrimp options would I would be back more regularly. There's also no alcohol served and its not BYOB. That said I'm looking forward to my next meal at Çka Ka Qellu and am still thinking about those dumplings and homemade "bread."

in the Arthur Ave area of the Bronx this intimate family run Albanian restaurant is the best. What makes New York great is when immigrants share their culture, especially food with all of us. The Cka Ka Qellu restaurant is proof of that! Authentic Albanian food and environment transports you to this mediterranean country.  Very family oriented, family style dishes are wonderful to share. If you're visiting the Bronx and need a place to eat this should be #1 on your list. If you're not visiting the Bronx, but want something outside of the typical offerings, this should also be at the top of your list. It's unique in every way from the cuisine to the decor and furnishings. The food is spectacular and our waitress was patient and very helpful with suggestions.  I'd suggest eating family style as you'll want to try everything like the traditional meat platter and various dips which go well with the homemade bread and the meats. The kajmak was my favorite of the dips as it's basically a perfect combination of rich, fatty, savory, creamy, & cheesy. The mantia were my standout surprise as veal dumplings that tasted a bit like burek served on dollops of yogurt crema. Would strongly suggest ordering the above on your first visit.  Lastly, I need to mention the baklava since I was raised by a mother who makes the best baklava. Usually, baklava is too sweet and often too doughy for me to enjoy, but this place nails it on the sweetness and does a good enough job with the texture.

The food is simply amazing.  I am a vegetarian for 30 years and I still eat the meet patties at Cka ka qellu.   The food is traditional to Albanian regions; a combination of foods that can not be found anywhere else but back home.  Every visit is an experience.  I love it that it’s a family place. I usually dont write reviews , but it was worth every single word for this place.
